<TITLE> Garment workers block highway for wages </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Gazipur, Jan 15 (bdnews24.com)Readymade garment workers blocked the Dhaka-Mymensingh highway for one and a half hours at Tongi on Friday demanding payment of pending salary and wages. Nippon Garment workers also demanded that the factory be reopened. Police and workers said that leaders of the Bangladesh Garment Manufacturers and Exporters Association, after a meeting with the factory owners on Jan 5, assured the workers of paying their arrears on Friday. According to that announcement, the workers started gathering in front of the factory from around 8am. The infuriated workers started demonstrating and barricaded the highway at 11 am as no BGMEA leaders or factory officials had showed up by then. United Garment Workers Federation president Ferdausi Begum said the BGMEA leaders and factory owners had been assuring the workers that all arrears would be cleared but it never quite came true. Later, at around 12.30pm, the workers withdrew their blockade upon assurance from the police. Gazipur assistant police superintendent Mohammed Monwar Hossain said the factory management had agreed to pay their workers a month's salary and a festival allowance. Nippon's sewing operator Shahnaj Begum and some other workers said the authorities served a notice on Oct 30 announcing closure from Nov 1 without consulting the workers. On the next day, three garment workers died in a clash with the police. The factory has remained closed since the
